<SiteShell
  title="How We Built Kecker"
  description="Step-by-step: how kecker.co was built with Astro 5, Cloudflare Pages, and a portable design system — written for Android developers new to web."
  ogType="article"
  {schema}>
  <article class="prose-page">
    <header class="prose-header">
      <span class="eyebrow">Behind the Build</span>
      <h1>How We Built kecker.co</h1>
      <p class="lede">A guide for Android developers stepping into web for the first time.</p>
      <p class="byline">Kecker · <time datetime="2025-04-22">April 22, 2025</time></p>
    </header>

    <div class="reading-body">

      <p>
        If you have shipped Android apps, you already know how to think in components, build systems,
        and deployment pipelines. The web uses different words for the same ideas. This post maps
        the concepts you already know onto the tools we used to build kecker.co, so you can read
        the codebase and understand every decision without having to learn web from scratch first.
      </p>

      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <h2>1. The Stack at a Glance</h2>

      <p>Here is everything involved in building and shipping kecker.co:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Astro 5</strong> — static site generator (the build system for HTML)</li>
        <li><strong>Cloudflare Pages</strong> — hosting and global CDN</li>
        <li><strong>Wrangler</strong> — Cloudflare's CLI deployment tool</li>
        <li><strong>GitHub</strong> — source code hosting and version control</li>
        <li><strong>EB Garamond + Inter</strong> — typefaces, loaded from Google Fonts</li>
        <li><strong>CSS custom properties</strong> — design tokens (colors, spacing, type scale)</li>
        <li><strong>Storybook</strong> — isolated component development environment</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        No React. No Vue. No Angular. No JavaScript framework at all. The site is plain HTML and CSS
        generated at build time. That is the whole point of static site generation, and we will get
        into exactly what that means.
      </p>

      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <h2>2. Astro: A Build System for HTML</h2>

      <p>
        Astro is a static site generator. The simplest way to understand it: Astro takes your source
        files and transforms them into plain HTML, CSS, and JavaScript files that any web server can
        serve. Think of it like Gradle, but instead of compiling Kotlin into an APK, it compiles
        <code>.astro</code> files into a <code>dist/</code> folder full of HTML files.
      </p>

      <p>
        In Android, your UI exists at runtime. Activities, Fragments, and Views are instantiated
        by the framework when the user launches your app, and the layout is inflated on-device.
        In Astro, there is no runtime. Pages, Layouts, and Components are rendered once during
        <code>npm run build</code>, and the output is a set of static files. When someone visits
        kecker.co, the server is not running any code. It just sends back a pre-built HTML file.
      </p>

      <p>
        The build command comparison is nearly one-to-one:
      </p>

      <pre><code># Android
./gradlew assembleRelease   → outputs build/outputs/apk/release/app-release.apk

# Astro
npm run build               → outputs dist/ folder full of .html files</code></pre>

      <p>
        Astro files end in <code>.astro</code> and have two sections. The top is a frontmatter
        block, wrapped in <code>---</code> delimiters, where you write TypeScript that runs at
        build time. Below the frontmatter is the HTML template. Think of the frontmatter like a
        Gradle build script: it runs during compilation, can import other modules, fetch data, and
        compute values that get injected into the HTML template below it.
      </p>

      <pre><code>---
// This TypeScript runs at build time, not in the browser
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
const title = "Hello from build time";
---

&lt;!-- This HTML is the output template --&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;&#123;title&#125;&lt;/h1&gt;</code></pre>

      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <h2>3. File Structure: How Routing Works</h2>

      <p>
        Astro uses file-based routing. Every <code>.astro</code> file inside <code>src/pages/</code>
        automatically becomes a URL. No router configuration. No manifest. No intent filters to
        register. Just put a file in the right folder.
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><code>src/pages/index.astro</code> → <code>kecker.co/</code></li>
        <li><code>src/pages/privacy.astro</code> → <code>kecker.co/privacy</code></li>
        <li><code>src/pages/404.astro</code> → served when any URL is not found</li>
        <li><code>src/pages/blog/how-we-built-kecker.astro</code> → <code>kecker.co/blog/how-we-built-kecker</code></li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        The Android analogy: in Android, each Activity declares which Intents it handles in
        <code>AndroidManifest.xml</code>. You explicitly register every screen. In Astro, the
        file path is the declaration. A file's location in <code>src/pages/</code> is its own
        routing configuration. Fewer places to look when something is broken.
      </p>

      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <h2>4. Layouts and Components: Like Fragments and ViewGroups</h2>

      <p>
        Almost every page on kecker.co starts with the same wrapper:
      </p>

      <pre><code>---
import SiteShell from '../layouts/SiteShell.astro';
---

&lt;SiteShell title="Page Title" description="..."&gt;
  &lt;!-- page content goes here --&gt;
&lt;/SiteShell&gt;</code></pre>

      <p>
        <code>SiteShell.astro</code> is the master layout. It wraps every page with the
        <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> tags, mounts the
        <code>Header</code> component at the top, and the <code>Footer</code> component at the
        bottom. Compare this to having a <code>BaseActivity</code> in Android that all your
        activities extend, automatically providing a toolbar and bottom navigation. Every page
        gets the site chrome without repeating it.
      </p>

      <p>
        Inside <code>SiteShell.astro</code>, there is a single <code>&lt;slot /&gt;</code> tag.
        This is the insertion point where child page content gets placed. Think of
        <code>&lt;slot /&gt;</code> as a <code>FrameLayout</code> in a base layout XML: it is the
        container that child Fragments (or in this case, page content) inflate into.
      </p>

      <p>
        Components like <code>Header.astro</code>, <code>Footer.astro</code>, and
        <code>BaseHead.astro</code> live in <code>src/components/</code>. They are reusable pieces
        of UI, exactly like custom Views or reusable Fragment classes in Android. The difference is
        that they produce HTML strings at build time rather than View objects at runtime.
      </p>

      <p>
        Components accept props, declared with a TypeScript interface at the top of the frontmatter:
      </p>

      <pre><code>---
interface Props &#123;
  title: string;
  description: string;
&#125;
const &#123; title, description &#125; = Astro.props;
---</code></pre>

      <p>
        This is the same pattern as passing a <code>Bundle</code> of extras to a Fragment, or
        exposing properties on a ViewModel. The parent passes values in; the component uses them
        to render its output.
      </p>

      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <h2>5. CSS: Like XML Layouts, But More Powerful</h2>

      <p>
        In Android, you define how things look in <code>res/layout/*.xml</code> and style them
        with <code>styles.xml</code> and <code>attrs.xml</code>. On the web, CSS handles all of
        that in one language. Instead of <code>android:textColor="#111111"</code>, you write
        <code>color: #111111</code>. Instead of <code>android:layout_marginTop="16dp"</code>,
        you write <code>margin-top: 16px</code>.
      </p>

      <p>
        CSS custom properties are the web equivalent of your <code>colors.xml</code> resource
        file. You define them once on the root element and reference them everywhere:
      </p>

      <pre><code>/* global.css */
:root &#123;
  --color-accent: #971b2f;
  --font-body: 'EB Garamond', serif;
  --space-lg: 2rem;
&#125;

/* Use them anywhere */
h1 &#123;
  color: var(--color-accent);
  font-family: var(--font-body);
  margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
&#125;</code></pre>

      <p>
        Change <code>--color-accent</code> in one place and every element that references it
        updates automatically. This is exactly how <code>@color/accent</code> works in Android
        resource references.
      </p>

      <p>
        Astro also scopes styles automatically. When you write a <code>&lt;style&gt;</code> block
        inside a <code>.astro</code> component, those styles only apply to that component's HTML.
        Astro achieves this by injecting a unique attribute (like <code>data-astro-cid-xxxxxx</code>)
        onto the component's elements and adding that attribute to all the CSS selectors at build
        time. It is similar to how a custom View in Android that draws its own background does not
        affect its neighbors. Styles stay local unless you explicitly make them global.
      </p>

      <p>
        Global styles live in <code>src/styles/global.css</code> and are the web equivalent of
        your base <code>AppTheme</code> in <code>styles.xml</code>. They set defaults for typography,
        spacing, and color that apply site-wide.
      </p>

      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <h2>6. The Design System: A tokens.ts Shared Resource</h2>

      <p>
        <code>src/design-system/tokens.ts</code> exports all color, font, and spacing values as
        TypeScript constants. Think of it as a <code>DesignTokens.kt</code> file in your Android
        project that defines every value in your Material theme, kept outside of XML so it can be
        referenced from code.
      </p>

      <pre><code>// tokens.ts
export const colors = &#123;
  accent: '#971b2f',
  ink: '#1a1a1a',
  paper: '#faf8f3',
&#125;;

export const fonts = &#123;
  serif: "'EB Garamond', Georgia, serif",
  sans: "'Inter', system-ui, sans-serif",
&#125;;</code></pre>

      <p>
        Both the CSS custom properties and the Storybook configuration pull values from this file.
        When you change a token here, every consumer updates. This is the single source of truth
        principle: design values live in one place, not scattered across multiple files where they
        can drift out of sync.
      </p>

      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <h2>7. The Logo: SVG Vector Format</h2>

      <p>
        The K mark is stored as an SVG file in <code>public/logo/</code>. SVG stands for Scalable
        Vector Graphics. It is the exact same concept as a Vector Drawable in Android: a resolution-
        independent format defined with mathematical paths rather than a fixed grid of pixels. It
        looks sharp at any size, from a 16px favicon to a full-screen display.
      </p>

      <p>
        The SVG uses <code>fill="currentColor"</code> on its path elements. This is a CSS keyword
        that means "inherit the text color from my parent." In CSS you can then write
        <code>color: white</code> on the parent element to make the logo white, or
        <code>color: var(--color-accent)</code> to make it the brand color. This is equivalent to
        applying <code>android:tint</code> programmatically, except it is pure CSS with no code
        required.
      </p>

      <p>
        The <code>public/</code> folder is Astro's equivalent of <code>res/raw/</code> or
        <code>res/drawable/</code>. Files placed there are copied directly to the output
        <code>dist/</code> folder without any processing or transformation. Static assets like
        fonts, images, and favicons live here.
      </p>

      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <h2>8. Storybook: Like a UI Component Gallery</h2>

      <p>
        Storybook is a development tool that lets you view and interact with individual components
        in isolation, without running the full site. You launch it with <code>npm run storybook</code>
        and it opens a local web app where every component is listed and rendered on its own.
      </p>

      <p>
        The Android parallel: imagine having a standalone debug app in your project that renders
        all your custom Views and Composables in a scrollable list, letting you tweak their props
        and see how they look in different states. No need to navigate through six screens to reach
        the component you are working on. Storybook is exactly that, for web components.
      </p>

      <p>
        Each file in <code>src/stories/</code> defines a "story": a specific rendered state of a
        component. A button story might show the default state, a loading state, and a disabled
        state side by side. This makes it easy to develop and review components without touching
        the rest of the site.
      </p>

      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <h2>9. Deployment: Cloudflare Pages Instead of Google Play</h2>

      <p>
        Google Play distributes APKs to users' devices. Cloudflare Pages distributes HTML, CSS,
        and JavaScript files to servers around the world. The concept is the same: you upload
        your built artifact to a distribution network, and users receive it from there.
      </p>

      <p>
        Cloudflare operates a global edge network, which is a CDN (Content Delivery Network).
        When a user in Tokyo visits kecker.co, Cloudflare serves the files from a data center near
        Tokyo rather than from wherever your origin server happens to be. This is similar to how
        Google Play mirrors APKs to regional servers so that downloads are fast regardless of
        where the user is located.
      </p>

      <p>
        Wrangler is the CLI tool for deploying to Cloudflare. It is the <code>bundletool</code>
        of the web world. After running <code>npm run build</code>, you deploy the output folder:
      </p>

      <pre><code>npx wrangler pages deploy dist --project-name kecker-docs</code></pre>

      <p>
        <code>dist</code> is the folder Astro wrote during the build step. <code>kecker-docs</code>
        is the name of the project in your Cloudflare Pages dashboard, which does not have to match
        your repository name. Wrangler uploads the files, Cloudflare propagates them to its edge
        nodes, and the new version is live within seconds.
      </p>

      <p>
        GitHub stores the source code, not the built output. Pushing to GitHub is your version
        control commit, not your deployment. The two steps are intentionally separate. Cloudflare
        can also be configured to auto-deploy whenever you push to a branch (continuous deployment),
        but the site currently deploys manually via the Wrangler command above.
      </p>

      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <h2>10. The Build-Deploy Cycle</h2>

      <p>
        Here is the full workflow from edit to live, written out as a recipe:
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li>Edit files in <code>src/</code>.</li>
        <li>
          Run <code>npm run dev</code>. This starts a local development server at
          <code>localhost:4321</code>. Like running the app in the Android Emulator: your
          changes appear in the browser instantly as you save files, no rebuild required.
        </li>
        <li>
          When you are happy with the changes, run <code>npm run build</code>. Astro compiles
          all pages and writes the output to <code>dist/</code>. This is your release build.
          Check <code>dist/</code> to confirm the files look right.
        </li>
        <li>
          Deploy to Cloudflare:<br />
          <code>npx wrangler pages deploy dist --project-name kecker-docs</code>
        </li>
        <li>
          Save to GitHub:<br />
          <code>git add . &amp;&amp; git commit -m "Your message" &amp;&amp; git push</code>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        Steps 4 and 5 are independent. Cloudflare does not know about GitHub unless you configure
        integration. Deploying to Cloudflare makes the site live. Pushing to GitHub saves your
        history. Both matter.
      </p>

      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <h2>11. What "Static Site Generation" Actually Means</h2>

      <p>
        There are two broad models for delivering web pages to users. The first: a server receives
        a request, runs code, builds an HTML response, and sends it back. This is what most app
        backends do. The second: HTML is generated once at build time from source files, the output
        is stored as plain files, and a server sends those files directly without running any code.
        Astro does the second.
      </p>

      <p>
        When someone visits kecker.co, Cloudflare sends back a pre-built HTML file from its edge
        node. There is no application server. No database query. No server-side code execution.
        Just a file transfer. This is extremely fast and costs almost nothing to operate.
      </p>

      <p>
        Here is the Android analogy that makes this click: imagine if, instead of inflating layouts
        at runtime, you pre-rendered every screen as a bitmap during the Gradle build and just
        displayed the right bitmap when the user navigated to that screen. No inflation, no binding,
        no layout pass. Just read a file and display it. That is static site generation. It works
        perfectly for content that is the same for every visitor, which describes a marketing and
        documentation site like kecker.co completely.
      </p>

      <p>
        The tradeoff: because everything is pre-built, pages cannot vary per user. There is no
        "show this user's name in the header." For that you would reach for a framework with
        server-side rendering. But for kecker.co, static is exactly the right choice.
      </p>

      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <h2>12. Where to Go From Here</h2>

      <p>
        If you want to go deeper on any of these topics, these are the resources worth your time:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong><a href="https://docs.astro.build" target="_blank" rel="noopener">docs.astro.build</a></strong>
          — the official Astro documentation. Well-written, with clear examples. Start with the
          "Getting Started" guide and the "Core Concepts" section.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><a href="https://web.dev" target="_blank" rel="noopener">web.dev</a></strong>
          — Google's web fundamentals guide. Particularly good for Android developers because it
          explains performance, layout, and CSS in terms that align with how mobile engineers
          already think. The "Learn CSS" course is excellent.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">developer.mozilla.org</a></strong>
          (MDN Web Docs) — the authoritative reference for every web API, CSS property, and HTML
          element. Think of it as the Android developer documentation, but for the web platform.
          Whenever you see an unfamiliar CSS property or HTML tag, MDN is the first place to look.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        The web platform is large, but the fundamentals are stable. HTML, CSS, and the idea that
        a URL maps to a file have not changed in thirty years. Once those are solid, every
        framework you encounter is just a different way of generating the same output.
      </p>

    </div>
  </article>
